Creating and Modifying Directories
1. mkdir: Creates a new directory.
Usage: mkdir <directory_path>
Example: mkdir /home/analyst/logs/network
Verify with: ls

2. rmdir: Removes an empty directory.
Usage: rmdir <directory_path>
Example: rmdir /home/analyst/logs/network

Creating and Modifying Files
1. touch: Creates a new, empty file.
Usage: touch <file_name>
Example: touch permissions.txt
Verify with: ls

2. rm: Removes a file.
Usage: rm <file_name>
Example: rm permissions.txt

Moving and Copying Files
1. mv: Moves or renames a file or directory.
Usage for moving: mv <source> <destination>
Usage for renaming: mv <old_name> <new_name>
Example for moving: mv permissions.txt /home/analyst/logs
Example for renaming: mv permissions.txt perm.txt

2.cp: Copies a file or directory.
Usage: cp <source> <destination>
Example: cp permissions.txt /home/analyst/logs

Editing Files with nano
1. nano: Command-line text editor for creating and editing files.
Open a file: nano <file_name>
Save changes: Ctrl + O, then confirm file name.
Exit: Ctrl + X
Example: nano permissions.txt

Standard Output Redirection
1. >: Redirects and overwrites output to a file.
Usage: command > <file>
Example: echo "time" > permissions.txt (overwrites the file)

2. >>: Redirects and appends output to a file.
Usage: command >> <file>
Example: echo "last updated date" >> permissions.txt (appends to the file)
